From the moment you listen to music, you encounter an unwavering wave of emotion. Whether it\rquote s a gut-wrenching movie or video game sequence, an annoyingly-memorable advertising jingle, or a blast from your childhood past, you felt (and probably still do feel) a certain way when hearing it. But what would happen if the instrument sounds of your favourite hits were suddenly swapped? It\rquote s widely (yet informally) known that major keys make happier melodies than minor keys (Jingle Bells in minor might sound like there\rquote s nothing in your stocking this year). Adjusting the song\rquote s scales or performance can shift the mood, depending on the extent of the change. But there\rquote s something about the sound of a low legato cello that speaks more to sadness, than a high jumpy marimba melody. To understand how sounds stir up emotions, let\rquote s examine what they\rquote re built upon.\par
\par
The truth is in the timbre\par
We call our subjective understanding of a sound\rquote s frequency spectrum timbre. Think of timbre as the sonic fingerprint, or quality of the sound. It\rquote s what makes you recognise a piccolo over a piano, regardless of the note being played.\par
\par
Each note played on an instrument has an identifiable pitch or tone. This is the fundamental frequency that is the central or most salient pitch of the note. On top of this \lquote fundamental\rquote  are a series of harmonics or \lquote partials\rquote  in a sequence. Take the note \lquote A\rquote , tuned to a frequency of 440Hz. The first partial would be the octave above, 440Hz times two, which is 880Hz. The next partial would be the fundamental times three, which is actually an interval of a \lquote fifth\rquote , in musical terms. The next partial is then the fundamental times four, two octaves above, and so on. What makes up the characteristic timbre of an instrument is the strength of the individual partials in relation to each other. Many different factors shape the strength of the partials, such as the physical material the instrument is made from, how that affects a resonating column of air, particular string vibration characteristics, or the loudness at which an instrument is played.\par
\par
Sound frequencies also develop over time. Plucking a string with a plastic guitar pick creates a short burst of noise, containing harmonic and inharmonic partials, which quickly fades out (within the first 30 ms), leaving room for the pure partials of the vibrating string. These also fade over time, from the highest frequency downwards. This whole \lquote envelope\rquote  is what gives a guitar string the initial \lquote plucky\rquote  attack, and why the sound softens over time; as its volume fades, so does its frequency spectrum. You\rquote ll see this in the spectrogram below, generated from a guitar string. A spectrogram shows the distribution of a sound\rquote s frequency spectrum over time. Frequency is mapped on the vertical axis, and time in seconds on the horizontal. The brighter the color, the higher the energy or amplitude of the frequency.\par
\par
