However, this isn\rquote t the case with all instruments. Wind instruments, for example, don\rquote t fade in timbre and volume over time in the same way, since they constantly need air blown through them to produce sound.\par
\par
Non-tonal sounds have much more complex timbre, but follow the same composition principles. We get vast amounts of information daily from simple object sounds, and can often derive the material, weight and/or size of an item just by listening. From experience, we\rquote ve learned to recognise a pencil hitting a wooden floor, or when a finger taps an empty plastic bottle \f1\emdash  by it\rquote s hollow roundedness. When describing timbres, we compare the sound\rquote s characteristics against objects we\rquote ve previously encountered in the world. Describing something as thin could refer to a sound \lquote not being full\rquote , or lacking a body that resonates with lower frequencies. Real world bass frequencies often come from \lquote big\rquote  materials, or larger resonating chambers. \lquote Thin\rquote  therefore refers to a smaller object, rather than a larger one with a \lquote bassy\rquote , \lquote deep\rquote  or \lquote full\rquote  sound.\par
\par
The first set of descriptors for different timbre groups was introduced by Hermann von Helmholtz back in 1877 (see the figure below, from Howard and Tyrell). We can see that different examples of grouped acoustic instruments are tied to specific descriptors, and how some of the descriptors are linked to an emotion.\par
\par
