Striations are frequencies above the 7th harmonic, where the spacing between the individual partials becomes harder for our ears to perceive. They\rquote re therefore perceived as noisy or harsher if they dominate.\par
\par
The human ear is very sensitive to transients; the \lquote attack\rquote  of a sound. The ability to hear rapid, sudden changes might\rquote ve granted us an evolutionary edge, as they\rquote re often associated with danger or a need to respond. Smaller or \lquote thinner\rquote  sounds might appear less threatening, because usually smaller things and animals aren\rquote t as dangerous (unless it\rquote s a Golden Poison Dart Frog), whereas a large bass-heavy object might be reminiscent of an incoming avalanche, which could be lethal. \lquote Pure\rquote  timbre tones, where \lquote even harmonics\rquote  dominate, provide a more round tone. For most people this might indicate friendliness, warmth or happiness, whereas odd harmonics with noisy content might be harsher on our ears and thus appear less friendly. Indeed, many of the above descriptors do somewhat describe the sensation of those timbres when we hear something as \lquote harsh\rquote  or \lquote round\rquote .\par
\par
Emotional response to timbre could also originate from how humans express and perceive emotions through timbral changes in the sounds of voices. When we\rquote re angry we might shout, becoming louder and distorting our vocals, with more partials, whereas tender emotion is more easily expressed in a quieter, softer and rounder sounding voice. Even the pitch of our voice reflects emotion \emdash  sadness is generally lower compared to a higher-pitched, happier voice.\par
\par
Various bodies of research show that different musical instruments evoke certain emotions. The reason for this is contested. The emotive connotations of instruments might be something we\rquote ve been \lquote taught\rquote  culturally by theatre or opera, and subsequently in films and games. However, there seem to be broader commonalities between emotions and the specific categories of timbre, which may apply cross-culturally. For example, slower attack and lower-register instruments with more striations, such as the cello and bassoon, are perceived as sadder compared to short-attack instruments, like a brighter-sounding xylophone.\par
\par
Picking timbre by instrumentation\par
Now that we\rquote ve looked at how different timbres can nudge sounds in specific emotional directions, let\rquote s look at how a musician can do this. Sergei Prokofiev, one of the world\rquote s greatest musicians, created \lquote Peter And The Wolf\rquote  (1936), a stunning example of characters represented by specific instruments to reflect their real-world sound. The specific timbre also hints at each character\rquote s unique personality, vocal characteristics, and role in the story. Birds are represented by the flute, a duck by the oboe, the wolf by the horns, and Peter, the protagonist, by strings.\par
\par
There\rquote s a more thorough technical explanation for this. The slightly more nasal quality of the oboe resembles a duck quacking, while the thin, bright flute sound is similar to birds twittering and chirping. Then you have the sneaky timbre of the clarinet, representing the cat. Finally, the howling, round, deep sound of three french horns and the slight dissonance between them creates a sensation of impending, ominous evil, representing the wolf. It\rquote s quite easy to hear the difference between a silver flute and a real bird chirping in the woods, but it\rquote s the feelings and associations we form when hearing them that matter. Of course, harmonic progressions and melodies also influence and evoke emotions, but an instrument\rquote s pure sound and the way it\rquote s played clearly demonstrate how we connect timbre to emotion.\par
\par
\par
A classic masterclass on character-based instrumentation.\par
Another well-known example that illustrates the intrinsic nature of music, emotion and character, within the context of less \lquote traditional\rquote  harmony, is the unsettling yet action-packed \lquote Joker\rquote s theme\rquote  by Hans Zimmer from the \lquote The Dark Knight\rquote . The piece places far more focus on the eeriness and dissonance of the instruments than Prokofiev\rquote s Peter and the Wolf. The main sound consists of one \lquote object\rquote : a layer of distorted guitars, cellos and recorded material, such as piano strings played using dull razor blades.\par
\par
The strings, partly distorted by effect processing and performance, keep the listener in an uneasy state of tense expectancy. Most people usually recognise how a string instrument is played, and can identify how the bow forces the tension on the strings. This is coupled with tremolo, a performative way of adding tension. These techniques present even more partials and harsh timbre, as we hear the instrument continuously pushed while the sound seemingly stretches. The harshness of metal against metal from the aforementioned razor blades, together with the distortion processing, enhance this raking feeling until we\rquote re sonically and mentally transported into the throes of a system that is working beyond its limits.\par
\par
This is the perfect instance of synchronisation of performance and effect processing to achieve appropriate emotion-evoking audio \emdash  the desired noisy, inharmonic timbre. Each sound is carefully layered together to create one artificial instrument, where beating frequencies, noises, and combinations of timbre create a complex unpleasantness, iconic of the tension and \lquote fear\rquote  central to the characters in the story.\par
\par
